message_1:
Consider the following system of linear equations:

\begin{cases} 2x + 5y - z = 5 \\ 3x - 2y + z = -3 \\ -x + y + 4z = 9 \end{cases}

Use block matrices to solve the system of equations and find the values of x, y, and z.

message_2:
To solve the system of linear equations using block matrices, we first represent the system as a matrix equation AX = B, where A is the matrix of coefficients, X is the column matrix of variables, and B is the column matrix of constants.

A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 5 & -1 \\ 3 & -2 & 1 \\ -1 & 1 & 4 \end{bmatrix}, X = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}, B = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}

Now, we need to find the inverse of matrix A, denoted as A^{-1}. To do this, we first find the determinant of A.

det(A) = 2(-8 - 1) - 5(-3 - 12) - (-1)(3 - 2) = 2(-9) - 5(-15) - (-1)(1) = -18 + 75 + 1 = 58

Since the determinant is non-zero, the inverse of A exists. Now, we find the adjugate of A and divide each element by the determinant to get A^{-1}.

adj(A) = \begin{bmatrix} -8 & -1 & 7 \\ -15 & -3 & 5 \\ 1 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}

A^{-1} = \frac{1}{58} \begin{bmatrix} -8 & -1 & 7 \\ -15 & -3 & 5 \\ 1 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}

Now, we can find the solution X by multiplying A^{-1} with B:

X = A^{-1}B = \frac{1}{58} \begin{bmatrix} -8 & -1 & 7 \\ -15 & -3 & 5 \\ 1 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}

X = \frac{1}{58} \begin{bmatrix} (-8)(5) + (-1)(-3) + 7(9) \\ (-15)(5) + (-3)(-3) + 5(9) \\ 1(5) + (-1)(-3) + 1(9) \end{bmatrix}

X = \frac{1}{58} \begin{bmatrix} -40 + 3 + 63 \\ -75 + 9 + 45 \\ 5 + 3 + 9 \end{bmatrix}

X = \frac{1}{58} \begin{bmatrix} 26 \\ -21 \\ 17 \end{bmatrix}

So, the solution to the system of linear equations is:

x = \frac{26}{58} = \frac{13}{29}
y = \frac{-21}{58}
z = \frac{17}{58}
